**Hydration** is a core concept in React and Next.js, especially when **Server‑Side Rendering (SSR)** is involved.

I’ll explain it **simply first**, then go a bit deeper so it fully clicks.

***

# ✅ What is Hydration? (Simple definition)

> **Hydration is the process where React takes server‑rendered HTML and “activates” it by attaching event handlers and state on the browser.**

In short:

*   Server sends **HTML**
*   Browser shows content **fast**
*   React then **hydrates** it to make it interactive

***

# 🧠 Why Hydration Exists

Without hydration, SSR would give you:

*   ✅ Fast initial page load
*   ❌ But **no interactivity** (buttons don’t work)

Hydration solves this by **reusing** the existing HTML instead of re‑creating it.

***

# ✅ Step‑by‑step: What actually happens

### 1️⃣ Server renders HTML (SSR)



User sees content immediately ✅

***

### 2️⃣ Browser downloads JS bundle

React code arrives in the browser.

***

### 3️⃣ React hydrates the page

React:

*   Matches the existing DOM
*   Attaches event listeners
*   Restores component state

```jsx
<button onClick={() => alert("Hi")}>
  Click me
</button>
```

Now the button works ✅\
👉 **This step is hydration**

***

# 🔁 Rendering vs Hydration (Key difference)

| Rendering         | Hydration            |
| ----------------- | -------------------- |
| Creates new DOM   | Reuses existing DOM  |
| Happens on server | Happens in browser   |
| Produces HTML     | Makes it interactive |

***

# ✅ Hydration in Next.js (important for your earlier questions)

### Timeline

    SSR (server)
      ⛔ Error Boundaries inactive

    HTML sent to browser

    Hydration (client)
      ✅ Error Boundaries ACTIVE
      ✅ Event handlers work

That’s why:

*   ❌ Error Boundaries don’t catch SSR errors
*   ✅ They catch errors **after hydration**

***

# ❗ What is a Hydration Mismatch?

A **hydration error** happens when:

> The HTML generated on the server is **different** from what React expects on the client.

### Example ❌

```tsx
function Time() {
  return <p>{Date.now()}</p>;
}
```

*   Server time ≠ Browser time
*   React sees mismatch
*   ❌ Hydration error

***

### ✅ Fixed version

```tsx
'use client';
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

function Time() {
  const [time, setTime] = useState<number | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    setTime(Date.now());
  }, []);

  return <p>{time}</p>;
}
```

***

# ✅ Hydration and Error Boundaries (important link)

| Stage            | Error Boundary works? |
| ---------------- | --------------------- |
| SSR              | ❌ No                  |
| During hydration | ✅ Yes                 |
| After hydration  | ✅ Yes                 |

So this statement is **correct**:

> ✅ *Error Boundaries handle errors that happen after hydration*

***

# ✅ Hydration in App Router vs Pages Router

| Router       | Hydration behavior                  |
| ------------ | ----------------------------------- |
| Pages Router | Whole page hydrates                 |
| App Router   | **Selective / streaming hydration** |

App Router can hydrate:

*   One route segment at a time
*   Even retry hydration (`reset()`)

***

# 🧪 Easy mental model

Think of hydration like:

> **Plugging electricity into a fully built house**

*   House (HTML) ✅ already there
*   Electricity (JS + React) 🔌 makes it usable

***

# ✅ One‑line takeaway

> **Hydration is when React turns server‑rendered HTML into a fully interactive web app in the browser.**

