Here’s a **clean, intuitive comparison of Hydration vs Re‑render**, with mental models and examples so the difference really sticks.

***

# ✅ Hydration vs Re‑render (React / Next.js)

## One‑line definitions

*   **Hydration** 👉 *React attaches behavior to existing server‑rendered HTML*
*   **Re‑render** 👉 *React computes UI again and updates the DOM*

They solve **very different problems**.

***

## 🧠 Mental model first

### Hydration

> “The HTML already exists — just wake it up.”

### Re‑render

> “Something changed — update the UI.”

***

## 🔁 Visual timeline

    SERVER
      React renders → HTML

    BROWSER
      Show HTML (static)
      ↓
      HYDRATION ✅
      ↓
    USER INTERACTION / STATE CHANGE
      ↓
      RE‑RENDER ✅

***

## 1️⃣ What is **Hydration**?

Hydration happens **once** (per page or segment).

### ✅ Purpose

*   Make server-rendered HTML **interactive**
*   Attach:
    *   Event handlers
    *   State
    *   Effects

### ✅ Happens:

*   In the **browser**
*   After SSR HTML is loaded
*   Before user interaction

### ✅ Key rule

> **Hydration reuses existing DOM**
> (no DOM creation)

***

### Example: Hydration

#### Server sends:



#### Client React code:

```jsx
<button onClick={() => alert("Hi")}>
  Click me
</button>
```

During hydration:

*   React **matches** existing `<button>`
*   Attaches `onClick`
*   ✅ No DOM replacement

***

## 2️⃣ What is **Re‑render**?

A re-render happens **many times** during the app lifecycle.

### ✅ Purpose

*   Reflect **state or prop changes**

### ✅ Triggered by:

*   `setState`
*   `useState`
*   `props` change
*   Context change

### ✅ Key rule

> **Re-render may update the DOM**
> (but only what changed)

***

### Example: Re‑render

```jsx
function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
      {count}
    </button>
  );
}
```

Clicking the button:

*   State changes
*   Component **re-renders**
*   DOM text updates (`0 → 1`)

***

## 3️⃣ Side‑by‑Side Comparison

| Aspect                   | Hydration           | Re‑render          |
| ------------------------ | ------------------- | ------------------ |
| Purpose                  | Activate HTML       | Update UI          |
| When                     | Once (initial load) | Many times         |
| Happens in               | Browser             | Browser            |
| Uses existing DOM?       | ✅ Yes               | ♻️ Diff-based      |
| Related to SSR?          | ✅ Yes               | ❌ No               |
| Triggered by             | Page load           | State/props change |
| Error Boundaries active? | ✅ Yes               | ✅ Yes              |

***

## 4️⃣ Important Rules (Interview gold ⭐)

### ✅ Hydration Rules

*   Happens **after SSR**
*   Must match server HTML exactly
*   Mismatch → hydration error

```tsx
❌ Date.now() during SSR
❌ Math.random()
❌ Browser-only APIs
```

***

### ✅ Re‑render Rules

*   Can happen without SSR
*   Safe to use browser APIs
*   Normal React lifecycle

***

## 5️⃣ Hydration ≠ Re‑render (common mistake)

❌ **Wrong**

> “Hydration is just the first render”

✅ **Correct**

> “Hydration attaches React to existing HTML, while re‑render updates UI after that.”

***

## 6️⃣ How Next.js makes this clearer

### Pages Router

*   Whole page hydrates at once
*   Re-renders normally after

### App Router (Next.js 13+)

*   **Selective hydration**
*   Server Components don’t hydrate
*   Client Components hydrate & re‑render

```tsx
// Server component (no hydration)
export default async function Page() {
  return <ClientButton />;
}

// Client component (hydrates + re‑renders)
'use client';
function ClientButton() {
  return <button>Click</button>;
}
```

***

## 7️⃣ Error Boundaries connection (from your earlier questions)

| Stage     | Caught by Error Boundary? |
| --------- | ------------------------- |
| SSR       | ❌ No                      |
| Hydration | ✅ Yes                     |
| Re‑render | ✅ Yes                     |

***

## ✅ Final takeaway

> **Hydration turns static HTML into an interactive React app once.\
> Re‑render updates the UI repeatedly as data changes.**

